You can use a more complex regular expression.

To match more than one set of characters, you can use the _|_, vertical-bar character.

_[Wikipedia &amp;ndash; Regular expression &amp;ndash; POSIX extended](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_expression#POSIX_extended)_.

&gt; _&quot;The choice (also known as alternation or set union) operator matches either the expression before or the expression after the operator. For example, abc|def matches &quot;abc&quot; or &quot;def&quot;.&quot;_

```java
String string = &quot;whatever&quot;;
Pattern pattern = Pattern.compile(&quot;abc|def|ghi&quot;);
Matcher matcher = pattern.matcher(string);
if (matcher.find()) System.out.println(&quot;matched:  &quot; + matcher.group());
```

Furthermore, if you have an array of strings, you can utilize the _[String#join](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html#join(java.lang.CharSequence,java.lang.CharSequence...))_ method to concatenate them, by a vertical-bar character.

```java
String string = &quot;whatever&quot;;
String[] strings = {
    &quot;abc&quot;, &quot;def&quot;, &quot;ghi&quot;, &quot;jkl&quot;, &quot;mno&quot;, &quot;pqr&quot;, &quot;stu&quot;, &quot;vwx&quot;, &quot;yz&quot;
};
Pattern pattern = Pattern.compile(String.join(&quot;|&quot;, strings));
Matcher matcher = pattern.matcher(string);
if (matcher.find()) System.out.println(&quot;matched:  &quot; + matcher.group());
```

